Crime Boss Putin
Moscow — Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden have unanimously concluded that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia's president Putin's biggest opponent and also the founder of the anti-corruption foundation.
Fortunately, since Navalny survived, the relationship between Russia and Germany does not deteriorate.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her view, the incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can, and must, respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation's findings prove that the Russian government is the culprit, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted, "There is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, head of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed it was an act by Western intelligence agencies, thereby damaging the credibility of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's claim is clearly baseless, but he also pointed out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
It is unreasonable to poison a well-known political opponent just before an upcoming election, especially using a nerve agent developed by the former Soviet Union.
Furthermore, the timing of the incident is particularly intriguing, especially since Belarusians are protesting against the August election in neighboring countries.
Additionally, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny incident was especially confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If it was indeed the Russian government that did it, as Germany claims, this assassination was a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics (the main rebel figure in the movie Star Wars), intervening in the US election, inciting street protests in France, enticing the UK to leave the EU, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, visionary, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill the Skripals and Navalny?
Why could Navalny flee to Germany, and why was he quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream 2 natural gas pipeline project to Germany is facing cancellation.
This assassination clearly backfired.
In fact, it has further fueled public opposition to the misconduct of the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, the claim that Western intelligence agencies are responsible is even more outrageous.
If such allegations are true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have revealed the fact about the nerve agent Novichok.
The more likely possibility is a conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's political circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to shut up before the election, or perhaps it was due to his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are very naive, and they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, but only a few participants knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the public investigation committee into the case of Mikhail Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning of Peter Verkhovtsev, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reported on judicial abuse in Russia.
We can trace this further back to 2006, when Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer, was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Like the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan, although she survived. Two years later, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death caused great damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin at all.
Whether Putin personally ordered it or not, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death was the desired outcome for the Kremlin, and pleasing the master Putin is the ultimate goal of the henchmen.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning fails, they will not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who seek proof of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless, the Kremlin is the real culprit.
Western countries must make clear statements, even if their own economy is affected, to impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All the responsibilities that occur in Russia are attributed to him alone.
